"rating":"3.5",
"reviewcomment":"I came into La Kitchen with high expectations and left pretty disappointed.  On the plus side, I really liked the design of the restaurant.  The lighting, tables and use of mirrors was cojonudo.  Also the wine list was pretty good, with a handful of good choices for 15-20 euro a bottle, which is a good price range for decent Ribera  Unfortunately, I think that is where the plus side for me ends.<br><br>Service - lento y flojo (slow and slack).  I love that waiters don&#39;t rush diners in Spain, but I didn&#39;t love that we had to practically beg for service here despite a whole gaggle of staff in the joint.<br><br>Food - very average and I went with a group of 8 and had a chance to try a lot of their dishes.  The options were pretty standard: Ensalada de Rucula, Foie, Filete de Ternera, Bacalao, Cordero.  I wasn&#39;t particularly impressed by any of them.  Just very average.<br><br>With all of the restaurant options in Madrid and particular in the hip Alsono Martinez area, I think it safe to say that I won&#39;t be the Duke of La Kitchen any time soon.",
