"ogimage":"http://s3-media3.ak.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/2GSjI612cpcGudpJOemlbg/l.jpg",
"rating":"4.0",
"reviewcomment":"Headline: It&#39;s Madrid - It&#39;s Seafood - It&#39;s Good<br><br>A French guy, a British guy, a couple of Swedish guys and a couple of Germans walk into a Spanish fish restaurant.  This has all the hallmarks of a bad joke, but it was really good food.  As a transplanted Brit living in the middle of the US, I miss good fish, and I try to eat it when I can.<br><br>Appetizers are served family style.  we had a number of them, all seafood based.  My favorite were the clams.  They had a hake croquette that wasn&#39;t up to the standard of the other items.  It was small and crunchy and didn&#39;t have much flavor.<br><br>The star of the meal was a pair of hake baked under a salt dome.  This was delicious, and a definite must.  Each fish can server 3-4 people, so you won&#39;t go hungry.<br><br>Coming from the US, you have to realize that the Spanish eat later in the evening.  If you walk into a Spanish restaurant at six or seven o&#39;clock in the evening, you will have no problem getting a table.  If you go later, the place might fill up.  Also, drink the Spanish wines - they are superior to the other European wines in general and cheaper as well.  The local &#34;Mahou&#34; beer is the thing to get if you go that route.",
